This software is provided "AS IS" without warranty of any kind, either
expressed or implied.
@endnode

@node "Document_1" "Introduction"
@{b}Introduction@{ub} 

RelVel is a program which computes true wind speed and direction given the
measured relative wind speed & direction and the speed and heading of the
observer.  

I wrote this program to facilitate the calculation of true wind speeds &
directions during ship speed trials I am involved with.  It's far easier than
drawing vector diagrams (relvels) every time I need to know the true wind
conditions.

For background information, on completion of the ship speed trials the
affects of the wind on the ship's performance is just one of many correction
factors that is either added to or subtracted from the ship's average speed.

The original program was not written on my Amiga, but in BASIC on my Casio
fx-702p Pocket Computer (circa 1982).  It worked so well I decided to
transcribe it into C as well as Arexx.  The source is available upon
request.

There are no special requirements to use RelVel.  It should run on WB 1.3
although I haven't been able to test this.

I hope you find it useful.
@endnode

@node "Document_2" "Installation"
@{b}Installation@{ub}

There are no special installation instructions for RelVel.  Copy RelVel to
the directory of your choice; preferably in the command path - such as your c
directory.
@endnode

@node "Document_3" "Usage"
@{b}Usage@{ub}

@{u}Usage:@{uu}   relvel relv reldir vship shipshead
     
         where,
          
         relv = as measured relative wind velocity
               
         reldir = as measured relative wind direction (degrees)
               
         vship = velocity of observer
               
         shipshead = heading of observer (degrees)
     
 the units for velocity must be consistent; ie. don't use knots
 for relv and m/sec for vship.
                  
 @{u}Example:@{uu}
     
 What is the true wind speed and direction if the relative wind
 speed and direction were measured to be 20 knots at 90 degrees
 from a ship travelling at 15 knots at a heading of 270 degrees.
         
 @{u}Solution:@{uu}
     
 from the command line enter:
          
 'relvel 20 90 15 270'
          
 which gives the solution as:
          
 'True Wind Speed = 25.00 at 36.87 degrees'


@{u}Note:@{uu}

A vector diagram is enclosed in the distribution (relvel.iff) which may
assist in understanding the way in which the program works.
@endnode

